<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,746,1932]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,271,746,772]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Species of medium size (4.5–5.0 mm), distinguished by a strongly transverse rostrum with sides evidently convergent apicad, by moderately large, subspherical eyes hardly projecting beyond genae and by elytra rounded at sides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,746,1932]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,372,866,892]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Redescription</emphasis>
. Body outline not very elongate, widest across humeral calli. Dorsal vestiture formed by rounded scales, pale with bronze shimmer, some darker scales forming irregular elytral patches, and by short setae, widened at apex, reclinate on declivity. Rostrum strongly transverse, sides evidently convergent apicad, epistome not notched, epistomal keel present, pterygia more or less prominent. Frons wide, more than two thirds wider than metarostrum, with a median fovea. Eyes rounded, subspherical. Antennae with scape moderately narrow, strongly curved in basal half, scarcely incrassate from base to apex, funicle elongate, all desmomeres longer than wide, not or hardly widened progressively towards club, desmomere 2 a little shorter than 1; club rather elongate, first segment widely cup-shaped. Pronotum transverse, weakly rounded at sides. Elytra rounded at sides, progressively narrowing from humeral calli to apex, striae with evident punctures in spite of vestiture, each puncture with an elongate microseta, interstriae weakly convex. Tibiae elongate, protibiae more or less straight on outer margin, usually rounded at apex. Aedeagus in dorsal view cordiform in outline in pre-apical region (
<figureCitation box="[484,585,1306,1332]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–23" captionStartId="63.[151,269,1971,1995]" captionTargetBox="[206,1384,155,1958]" captionTargetId="figure-52@63.[200,1387,149,1961]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 22–23. 22. Pseudomeira quadraticollis: a. apex of aedeagus, dorsal view; b. endophallic structures. 23. Pseudomeira inviridis: a. apex of aedeagus, dorsal view; b. endophallic structures. Scale: 0.15 mm (a); 0.10 mm (b)." pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 23a</figureCitation>
); endophallic structures as in 
<figureCitation box="[934,1035,1306,1332]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–23" captionStartId="63.[151,269,1971,1995]" captionTargetBox="[206,1384,155,1958]" captionTargetId="figure-52@63.[200,1387,149,1961]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 22–23. 22. Pseudomeira quadraticollis: a. apex of aedeagus, dorsal view; b. endophallic structures. 23. Pseudomeira inviridis: a. apex of aedeagus, dorsal view; b. endophallic structures. Scale: 0.15 mm (a); 0.10 mm (b)." pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 23b</figureCitation>
. Spermatheca as in 
<figureCitation box="[1267,1368,1306,1332]" captionStart="FIGURE 51" captionStartId="78.[151,255,1871,1895]" captionTargetBox="[212,1367,212,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-39@78.[212,1375,194,1848]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURE 51. Spermatheca: a. Pseudomeira grenierii; b. P. tenuicornis; c. P. quadraticollis; d. P. inviridis. Scale: 0.10 mm." pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 51d</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
